description:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About us&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Health Education England’s vision is that everyone associated with health care will be committed to a lifetime of professional development, be proud of the care they provide, support and challenge one another and strive for ever-increasing standards of patient-centred care.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;HEE supports the delivery of high quality care for patients and high quality public health services by ensuring that the health workforce has the right skills, behaviours and training, and that health care staff are available in the right numbers to meet the needs of the public. It takes on leadership and oversight of healthcare workforce planning and will also be responsible for supporting and authorising Local Education and Training boards. HEE will maintain an effective system for professional education and training as part of a comprehensive health service.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About the role&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Education Programme Officer - Agenda for Change Band 5 – full-time (37.50 hours per week)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Are you a hard working individual with a positive approach to providing an excellent customer service? Can you make a difference? An exciting career opportunity has arisen in the Winchester office within Health Education England for a full time Education Programme Officer, with a strong focus on academic training, supporting recruitment for the academic programmes across foundation and speciality, and programme management support for primary care.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the Wessex local office of Health Education England, we are responsible for the planning, development, education and training of the healthcare and public health workforce across Hampshire, Dorset, Isle of Wight, Salisbury and the States of Jersey, supporting postgraduate medical and dental education and training for over 2,500 trainees. Based in Otterbourne, Winchester, we are seeking an enthusiastic and highly motivated individual who can demonstrate the key values of the NHS Constitution to provide a full and comprehensive front line administrative service within the team.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is an interesting and varied role where you will work in a challenging, busy and rewarding environment, as part of a friendly and supportive team. You will be building relationships and networks with a wide range of people including NHS hospital Trusts, GP practices, junior doctors, consultants, and the Royal Medical Colleges.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Education Programme Officer role has a varied portfolio which includes: -&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Programme lead for academic training:
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Recruitment&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Quarterly monitoring linking with the Postgraduate Medical Business Team&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Liaison with University and National Institute for Health Research (NIHR)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Working across the Postgraduate Medical Team functions to ensure that the NIHR processes are adhered to in a consistent manner&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Programme Management support for primary care
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Leading on a geographical area within the primary care portfolio&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You should be well-organised with the ability to manage and prioritise your workload and work with limited supervision. The postholder will also be a team player, supporting colleagues and contributing to the team’s broader running, outputs and progression.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You will need to demonstrate the ability to consistently deliver a high standard of work to tight deadlines.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Strong Word, Excel, Outlook and PowerPoint skills are also required.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We invest in training and development to make sure our staff are equipped with the right skills and knowledge to cope with the demands of the role. We fully support our staff in progressing and can offer further workplace training to help your career development.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We offer a pleasant, modern working environment with good public transport links and free on-site parking.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Further details of the role can be found in the recruitment profile&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Applicants will commence at the bottom of Band 5 with a full-time starting salary of £24,907, with pay step increases after 2 years’ service and 4 years’ service.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;These salaries are offered in accordance with NHS Terms and Conditions and the HEE Pay Progression Policy and are subject to annual cost of living review.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;If you like what you have read and think you have the skills and experience we need then don&#39;t delay, apply today! We get lots of applications for our roles and so we sometimes have to close our posts early. Don&#39;t miss out! &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For further details / informal visits contact:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Fenella Williams&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Education Programme Team Manager&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;01962 690359&lt;/p&gt;
